 a 3rd (variants sus2, m3, 3 or sus4), which can be considered as a triad w=
ith omitted 5th. Or just root and 5th, which is called a "e;power chord"e;.=
</p> 	<p>*) Examples: If a chord would contain a minor 3rd and a perfect 4t=
h, they cannot be represented as m3 and 4 in the same chord symbol. The 4 w=
ould then be considered as an extension 11! If you had a major 3rd (3) and =
a minor 3rd (m3) in one chord, the major 3rd would be considered as the 3rd=
 while the minor 3rd would be considered as altered tension #9.</p> </div><=
