t">                 <div class=3D"klapp accElem accClose" id=3D"ana_accordi=
on2_5">                     <h4 class=3D"accElemH" style=3D"position: relat=
ive;">Altered Tensions<div class=3D"openclose"><svg id=3D"svgopenclose" vie=
wBox=3D"0 0 20 20" class=3D"useopenclose">
<path d=3D"M4 13 L10 6 L16 13" fill=3D"none" stroke-width=3D"3" stroke-line=
cap=3D"round"></path>
</svg></div><div class=3D"keepopen"><svg id=3D"svgpin" viewBox=3D"0 0 20 20=
" class=3D"usepin">
<path d=3D"M2 10 L10 10" stroke-width=3D"1" stroke-linecap=3D"round"></path=
>
<circle class=3D"pinball" cx=3D"14" cy=3D"10" r=3D"3" stroke-width=3D"2"></=
circle>
</svg></div></h4>                     <div class=3D"accContent accElemConte=
nt">                     <p>Those are the tensions b9, #9, #11 and b13. V7 =
(dominant 7th) chords, which resolve to a I chord (with the root a 5th belo=
w the root of the V7 chord), are often extended by a b9, #9 and/or b13 to c=
reate more tension as with the natural tensions 9 or 13.</p>               =
      <p>Secondary dominants, which derive from chords that have altered te=
nsions by nature (e.g. if IIIm<sup>7</sup> is changed to III<sup>7</sup>) c=
an also have altered tensions, even if they don't resolve from V to I.</p> =
                    <p>The #11 often extends dominant 7th chords that are n=
ot located on the V<small>th</small> or III<small>rd</small> scale degree a=
nd where the other (alternatively usable) tensions 9 and 13 would NOT be al=
tered. 9 and #11 are often combined. Maj7 chords can also extended with a #=
11 if that <em>lydian</em> sound is desired.</p>                     </div>=
                 </div>                 <div class=3D"klapp accElem accClos=
e" id=3D"ana_accordion2_6">                     <h4 class=3D"accElemH" styl=
e=3D"position: relative;">Diminished 5th and Augmented 5th<div class=3D"ope=
nclose"><svg id=3D"svgopenclose" viewBox=3D"0 0 20 20" class=3D"useopenclos=
e">
<path d=3D"M4 13 L10 6 L16 13" fill=3D"none" stroke-width=3D"3" stroke-line=
cap=3D"round"></path>
</svg></div><div class=3D"keepopen"><svg id=3D"svgpin" viewBox=3D"0 0 20 20=
" class=3D"usepin">
<path d=3D"M2 10 L10 10" stroke-width=3D"1" stroke-linecap=3D"round"></path=
>
<circle class=3D"pinball" cx=3D"14" cy=3D"10" r=3D"3" stroke-width=3D"2"></=
circle>
</svg></div></h4>                     <div class=3D"accContent accElemConte=
nt">                     <p>b5 and #5 are enharmonic equivalents to #11 and=
 b13. While in dominant 7th chords #11 and b13 are usually preferable, b5 c=
an most likely be found in m7b5 (half-diminished) chords, and #5 often crea=
tes an intended tension in maj7#5 chords. Although not recommended here in =
most cases, V<sup>7b5</sup> or V<sup>7#5</sup> can be found quite frequentl=
y. When improvising you=E2=80=99d most likely use <em>Mixolydian #11</em> o=
r <em>Harmonic/Melodic Minor 5</em> (includes b13) over these chords, which=
 indicates that V<sup>7#11</sup> respectively V<sup>7b13</sup> is preferabl=
e.</p>                     </div>                 </div>                 <d=
iv class=3D"klapp accElem accClose" id=3D"ana_accordion2_7">               =
      <h4 class=3D"accElemH" style=3D"position: relative;">add (add9, add11=
, etc.)<div class=3D"openclose"><svg id=3D"svgopenclose" viewBox=3D"0 0 20 =
20" class=3D"useopenclose">
<path d=3D"M4 13 L10 6 L16 13" fill=3D"none" stroke-width=3D"3" stroke-line=
cap=3D"round"></path>
</svg></div><div class=3D"keepopen"><svg id=3D"svgpin" viewBox=3D"0 0 20 20=
" class=3D"usepin">
<path d=3D"M2 10 L10 10" stroke-width=3D"1" stroke-linecap=3D"round"></path=
>
<circle class=3D"pinball" cx=3D"14" cy=3D"10" r=3D"3" stroke-width=3D"2"></=
circle>
</svg></div></h4>                     <div class=3D"accContent accElemConte=
nt">                     <p>While the extension number includes a 7th and (=
theoretically) optionally includes all lower natural tensions (e.g. 13 opti=
onally includes 9 or 11), the litaral <em>add</em> adds the named tension w=
ithout a 7th and without including other tensions.</p>                     =
</div>                 </div>                 <div class=3D"klapp accElem a=
ccClose" id=3D"ana_accordion2_8">                     <h4 class=3D"accElemH=
" style=3D"position: relative;">omit/no<div class=3D"openclose"><svg id=3D"=
svgopenclose" viewBox=3D"0 0 20 20" class=3D"useopenclose">
<path d=3D"M4 13 L10 6 L16 13" fill=3D"none" stroke-width=3D"3" stroke-line=
cap=3D"round"></path>
</svg></div><div class=3D"keepopen"><svg id=3D"svgpin" viewBox=3D"0 0 20 20=
" class=3D"usepin">
<path d=3D"M2 10 L10 10" stroke-width=3D"1" stroke-linecap=3D"round"></path=
>
<circle class=3D"pinball" cx=3D"14" cy=3D"10" r=3D"3" stroke-width=3D"2"></=
circle>
</svg></div></h4>                     <div class=3D"accContent accElemConte=
nt">                     <p>Not playing a certain chord tone does not neces=
sarily lead to a different (and maybe more complicate) chord symbol. You ca=
n name the chord interval (without specifing whether the interval is minor,=
 major, diminished or augmented) with the prefix <em>omit</em> or just <em>=
no</em>. The least is preferable, if you analyze a played chord, but you do=
n't feel it's necessary to play it that way in general.</p>                =
     <p>Common example: Csus2 can often be seen as C(add9,omit3) respective=
ly C(add9,no3) chord. While notating sus2 can be dangerous, because some mu=
sicians might switch to a not intended sus4 chord here. Writing add9no3 is =
often closer to what it really is, since having the 3rd in the chord doesn=
=E2=80=99t sound wrong here.</p>                     </div>                =
 </div>             </div> <!-- End #accordion2 -->         </div>         =
<div class=3D"klapp accElem accClose" id=3D"ana_accordion1_10">            =
 <h3 class=3D"accElemH" style=3D"position: relative;">5. Bass (Slash Chord)=
<div class=3D"openclose"><svg id=3D"svgopenclose" viewBox=3D"0 0 20 20" cla=
ss=3D"useopenclose">
<path d=3D"M4 13 L10 6 L16 13" fill=3D"none" stroke-width=3D"3" stroke-line=
cap=3D"round"></path>
</svg></div><div class=3D"keepopen"><svg id=3D"svgpin" viewBox=3D"0 0 20 20=
" class=3D"usepin">
<path d=3D"M2 10 L10 10" stroke-width=3D"1" stroke-linecap=3D"round"></path=
>
<circle class=3D"pinball" cx=3D"14" cy=3D"10" r=3D"3" stroke-width=3D"2"></=
circle>
</svg></div></h3>             <div class=3D"accContent accElemContent">    =
         <p>Sometimes it seems reasonable to consider a different tone than=
 the lowest as the chords root. That can lead to a cleaner chord symbol or =
a more comprehensible chord progression. If we still want to have that lowe=
st note as our bass note, we can add it to the chord symbol after a slash. =
A chord written that way is called a <em>slash chord</em>.</p>             =
<p>Common examples: G/B or C/E. Progressions: C G/B Am, Fmaj7 C/E Dm7.</p> =
            </div>         </div>     </div> <!-- End #accordion1 --> </div=
> <!-- End #two -->  <div id=3D"three"> 	<p class=3D"repeatedH2">Chord name=
 evolution: triad =E2=86=92 7th chord =E2=86=92 extended chord</p>     <!--=
 Continiously and irregularly extending chord names --> 	<p>The quality of =
the basic triad does not change, whatever you add to the chord. 	 But the w=
ay the quality is notated in the chord name may change.</p>      <!-- In th=
e abstract above you can see 	Quality deduced from triad, but implicates us=
e (or no use) of certain type of 7 --> 	<table class=3D"qualityTable"><tbod=
y><tr><th>Quality Type</th><th>Triad<br>notation</th><th>with<br>6th/dim7</=
th><th>width<br>minor 7th</th><th>width<br>major 7th</th></tr> 	<tr><td>min=
or triad</td><td>m</td><td>m6</td><td>m7</td><td>m<sup>maj7</sup></td></tr>=
 	<tr><td>major triad</td><td></td><td>6</td><td>7</td><td>maj7</td></tr> 	=
<tr><td>sus2 triad</td><td>sus2</td><td><small>6sus2<br>6/9(no3)<small></sm=
all></small></td><td><small>7sus2</small></td><td><small>maj7sus2<br>maj9(n=
o3)</small></td></tr> 	<tr><td>sus4 triad</td><td>sus4</td><td><small>6sus4=
<small></small></small></td><td>7sus4</td><td><small>maj7sus4</small></td><=
/tr> 	<tr><td>diminished triad</td><td>dim</td><td>dim or dim7</td><td>m7b5=
</td><td><small>m<sup>maj7(#11)</sup></small></td></tr> 	<tr><td>augmented =
triad</td><td>aug</td><td><small>aug6</small></td><td>7(#5), <small>aug7</s=
mall></td><td>maj7(#5)</td></tr> 	</tbody></table> 	<p>While sus2 and sus4 =
chords are just slighly irregular by switching the position between quality=
 and extension number, the literal dim is replaced by mb5 when adding a min=
or 7th to it and for aug you'll write a major chord with a #5. To write aug=
7 respectively +7 is only common with a minor 7th.</p> 	<p>The literal <em>=
dim</em> implies the use of a diminished 7th (dim7). Actually you would wri=
te <em>dim</em> as quality for the diminished triad and <em>dim7</em> in su=
perscript for the diminished 7th. But we only have to write <em>dim</em> on=
ce. So <em>dim</em> or <em>dim7</em> is actually a shorthand notation for <=
em>dim<sup>dim7</sup></em>.</p> </div> <!-- End #three --> </div> <!-- End =
#accordion1 -->   <!-- End #iframecontent --> <!-- <div id=3D"svgbox" class=
=3D"outside"></div> --></div></div>
